body:
**Description**

I've discovered a way to cause SkiaSharp 1.68 to consistently crash in a multi-threaded environment with a System.AccessViolationException: 'Attempted to read or write protected memory. This is often an indication that other memory is corrupt.' The stack trace shows the crash is occuring when SKPictureRecorder is disposed. It's easy to reproduce using SkiaSharp.Extended.Svg, since it's powered by the picture recorder underneath the hood.

```
 	[Managed to Native Transition]	
 	SkiaSharp.dll!SkiaSharp.SKPictureRecorder.Dispose(bool disposing)	Unknown
 	SkiaSharp.dll!SkiaSharp.SKNativeObject.Dispose()	Unknown
 SkiaSharp.Extended.Svg.dll!SkiaSharp.Extended.Svg.SKSvg.Load(System.Xml.Linq.XDocument xdoc)	Unknown
```

**Code**

Create a new .NET Core or .NET Framework Console application. I reproduced it with both Core 2.1 and Framework 4.7.2. Add SkiaSharp 1.68 and SkiaSharp.Extended.Svg 1.60 from NuGet. You'll need a valid SVG of some sort; I just grabbed a free sample from w3.org. Then just paste in this main function to run a bunch of threads at once. Run it and it will crash immediately.

If you don't actually create a canvas right afterward, it won't crash either. Something terrible is happening behind the scenes with the SKPictureRecorder disposal and the SKCanvas disposal. Unfortunately, if you want to actually do something with the SVG afterwards in a real program you kinda need to make a canvas eventually.

Luckily, if you wrap the svg.Load in a lock, the program appears to complete successfully. Ideally though this wouldn't be necessary....

```
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Xml;
using SkiaSharp;

namespace TestApp {
	class Program {

		private static object _skSvgLock = new object();

		static void Main(string[] args) {
			Console.WriteLine($"Framework App {(IntPtr.Size == 8 ? "x64" : "x86")}");
			const int maxThreads = 100;
			const int maxRuns = 1000;

			Action targetRun = SvgRun;

			var sw = System.Diagnostics.Stopwatch.StartNew();

			var l = new List<System.Threading.Thread>();
			for (var i = 0; i < maxThreads; i++) {
				var t = new System.Threading.Thread((threadId) => {
					for (var j = 0; j < maxRuns; j++) {
						targetRun();
					}
				});
				t.Name = $"Thread #{i}";
				t.Start(i);
				l.Add(t);
			}
			for (var i = 0; i < maxThreads; i++) {
				l[i].Join();
			}

			sw.Stop();
			Console.WriteLine($"{sw.Elapsed:c}");
		}

		private static void SvgRun() {

			var bmp = ToBitmap(24, 24);
			bmp?.Dispose();

			SkiaSharp.SKBitmap ToBitmap(int width, int height) {
				SkiaSharp.SKPicture picture = null;
				try {
					var xDoc = ToXmlDocument(GetSvgText());

					//lock (_skSvgLock) {
					var svg = new SkiaSharp.Extended.Svg.SKSvg();
					using (var xr = new System.Xml.XmlNodeReader(xDoc)) {
						picture = svg.Load(xr);
					}
					//}

					var info = new SkiaSharp.SKImageInfo(width, height, SkiaSharp.SKColorType.Bgra8888, SKAlphaType.Premul);
					var bitmap = new SkiaSharp.SKBitmap(info);

					//The important line that causes the crash:
					using (var canvas = new SkiaSharp.SKCanvas(bitmap)) { }

					return bitmap;
				} finally {
					picture?.Dispose();
				}
			}

			XmlDocument ToXmlDocument(string svg) {
				var xDoc = new XmlDocument();
				using (var sr = new System.IO.StringReader(svg)) {
					xDoc.Load(sr);
				}
				return xDoc;
			}
			string GetSvgText() {
				return "<svg xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' viewBox=\"0 0 131 76\"><path d=\"M36,5l12,41l12-41h33v4l-13,21c30,10,2,69-21,28l7-2c15,27,33,-22,3,-19v-4l12-20h-15l-17,59h-1l-13-42l-12,42h-1l-20-67h9l12,41l8-28l-4-13h9\" fill='#005A9C'/><path d=\"M94,53c15,32,30,14,35,7l-1-7c-16,26-32,3-34,0M122,16c-10-21-34,0-21,30c-5-30 16,-38 23,-21l5-10l-2-9\"/></svg>";
			}
		}
	}
}
```

**Expected Behavior**

Expected no unmanaged memory corruption.

**Actual Behavior**

Got unmanaged memory error and potential process teardown.

**Basic Information**

- Version with issue:  1.68.0
- Last known good version:  Unknown
- IDE:  VS2019
- Platform Target Frameworks: 
- Windows Classic:  Core 2.1 & Framework 4.7.2
- Target Devices:   Windows 10 1903

